Drive and the SDK and why we

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:16.560
think the SDK is an important
part of the product.

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:19.170
So Drive itself, when I think
about Drive, I like to

00:01:19.170 --> 00:01:21.490
describe it along three
main features,

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:22.700
or three main pillars.

00:01:22.700 --> 00:01:24.965
You saw a little bit of this in
Clay's demo in the keynote,

00:01:24.965 --> 00:01:27.270
but we'll kind of go through
this, and as we go through

00:01:27.270 --> 00:01:29.680
these things you'll see why
overlaying an SDK over the top

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:31.350
of these things can be such
a powerful thing.

00:01:31.350 --> 00:01:34.350
But the first pillar is this
idea of access anywhere, and I

00:01:34.350 --> 00:01:37.210
think you saw that demonstrated
very well today.

00:01:37.210 --> 00:01:40.030
No matter where you are, we have
given you access to the

00:01:40.030 --> 00:01:41.920
content you have put in
Drive, so we do this

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:42.860
through a number of ways.

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:45.810
The first is through the web
UI at drive.google.com.

00:01:45.810 --> 00:01:47.910
Everything in your drive is
available to you through any

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:50.540
web browser that we support, and
you can do everything you

00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:52.760
need to do there through the
web-- you can share, you can

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:55.270
manage your files, you can
collaborate on them with

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:57.230
Google Docs, you can do a whole
number of things through

00:01:57.230 --> 00:01:58.210
the web UI.

00:01:58.210 --> 00:01:59.480
There's also the sync clients.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:02.840
We have sync clients now for Mac
and Windows, and the sync

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:05.820
client is a really terrific
piece of software that you

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:08.150
install on your desktop machine,
and it's going to

00:02:08.150 --> 00:02:10.490
sync content on your desktop
machine back and

00:02:10.490 --> 00:02:11.550
forth to the cloud.

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:14.070
So changes you make locally will
be reflected back in the

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:16.470
cloud, and changes you make in
the cloud are broadcast back

00:02:16.470 --> 00:02:17.960
down to your local machine.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:20.570
So wherever you have these sync
clients installed, all of

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:23.390
your content will always be up
to date across all of your

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:24.350
different machines.

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.580
And we also have
mobile devices.

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:28.890
Native apps on mobile devices,
we just announced that the iOS

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:31.720
app is available today on iPads,
iPods, pretty much any

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:32.780
iOS device.

00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:36.000
We have mobile devices on
Android, and now we also have

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.290
Drive integration built directly
into Chrome OS, so

00:02:38.290 --> 00:02:40.580
virtually any device you're
working on you're going to be

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:42.900
able to access your content
there and interact with it in

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:45.340
meaningful ways.

00:02:45.340 --> 00:02:47.130
The next thing is Drive
is really all about

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:47.840
collaboration.

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:50.210
It's not just about storing
things, it's about giving you

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:53.290
ways to work with other people
on the content in Drive.

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:55.740
So there's three main ways we
allow you to do this, and then

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:57.610
at the end of the presentation
we'll talk about some really

00:02:57.610 --> 00:02:59.200
exciting things coming
in this space.

00:02:59.200 --> 00:03:01.750
But the first one of these
things is sharing.

00:03:01.750 --> 00:03:04.600
In Drive, we let you share
content with people for a

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:07.410
variety of different ways-- you
can make content public,

00:03:07.410 --> 00:03:09.650
you can share content with large
groups of people through

00:03:09.650 --> 00:03:12.530
an unlisted link, you can share
directly with other

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:13.430
Drive users--

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:16.120
just adding them directly to the
content, and then only you

00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:18.680
and they can see it, or you can
even share it with groups.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:21.520
And when you do that sharing,
it's not just a blanket share,

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.940
you can decide what kind of
things that person can do with

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:25.740
the thing you're sharing.

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:28.670
So I can say, for instance, if
I shared something with John,

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:30.980
I probably don't want to let
him edit my file, he's not

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:32.350
really that reliable,
so I would just

00:03:32.350 --> 00:03:34.030
give him view access.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:36.090
Whereas other people you could
give edit access, or even

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:38.930
access to add comments, and
comments is the very next

00:03:38.930 --> 00:03:40.170
thing I want to talk
about here.

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:43.350
We now have given people that
use Drive the ability to add

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:45.460
comments to anything
in their drive.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:48.720
In the past, you could do that
for Google Docs, but arbitrary

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:49.770
files you couldn't.

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:53.820
Now you can add comments to any
file at all in Drive, and

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:57.170
so you could work together in
your team and add comments to

00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.240
things and collaborate on those
things all at once.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.640
And the last thing I want to
talk about in terms of

00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:04.320
collaboration is-- you saw
this today in the demo as

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:06.110
well-- is Google Docs,
of course.

00:04:06.110 --> 00:04:08.480
Google Docs allows you to
collaborate on a level that's

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:10.920
virtually unique across
this space.

00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:13.400
You can co-edit documents in
real time and everyone's

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:15.810
changes are automatically
broadcast to everyone else.

00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:18.000
If I'm working with John on
a document, I can see

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.290
immediately the changes he's
making to the document, so

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:23.710
it's an incredibly powerful
tool for collaboration.

00:04:23.710 --> 00:04:25.415
And then the last
thing is search.

00:04:25.415 --> 00:04:27.595
And I think this also came
across very well in the demo

00:04:27.595 --> 00:04:28.930
today as well.

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:31.410
If you talk about this for
images, it's a really cool

00:04:31.410 --> 00:04:34.550
thing, every image that is
uploaded into Drive we run

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:36.700
through the Google Goggles back
end, which is the same

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:39.150
technology that powers Google's
visual search.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:41.810
So this back end can recognize
a number of different things

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:43.940
in your images-- it can
recognize famous landmarks,

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:46.880
faces, corporate logos, and it
does a terrific job in doing

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:49.970
optical character recognition on
the content and the images.

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:52.620
So if you upload pictures
of mountains, or famous

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:54.050
landmarks, or buildings,
and you can

00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:55.130
search for those things.

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:57.600
The demo we like to do is Mount
Everest, we just upload

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:00.150
a ton of different pictures from
users of Mount Everest.

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:03.430
No metadata at all associated
with the image-- no file

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:06.340
names, no Exif, no geotagging,
nothing.

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:10.000
And Google Goggles can identify
them as pictures of

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.910
Everest, it's really quite
amazing to see.

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:15.710
So all that power of search
right there in

00:05:15.710 --> 00:05:18.420
Drive for you to do.

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:19.410
What we do then--

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:20.620
go ahead and click it--

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:22.810
is over the top of all of these
different services we

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:25.560
have overlaid in SDK, which
we're going to give developers

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.040
the ability to access all of
this technology, and John's

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:29.360
going to talk more about that.

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:32.970
JOHN DAY-RICHTER: So the Drive
SDK really cuts across all of

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:35.990
these three different pillars
of Google Drive, and makes

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:37.980
them available to
the applications

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:39.270
that you want to write.

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:42.890
And before we go into what the
Drive SDK does, we felt like

00:05:42.890 --> 00:05:45.880
we needed to explain why we
built an SDK at all because we

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.680
know we are not the only game in
town, and other people have

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:51.730
SDKs too, but we felt like there
were some things about

00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:54.910
our product that were so special
that it was important

00:05:54.910 --> 00:05:57.310
for us to make an SDK so that
other people could start

00:05:57.310 --> 00:05:59.940
writing apps on top of it.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:03.090
So first of all, with Google
Drive we wanted to make sure

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:06.220
that it wasn't just a place to
keep stuff, we wanted to make

00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:08.220
it a place to do stuff.

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:11.200
So no matter which of the Google
Drive clients you're

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:14.750
using, you can use your
file on that system.

00:06:14.750 --> 00:06:17.420
So if you're using the Google
Drive web client, you can do a

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:20.230
whole lot more than just
download the files that are in

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:21.480
Google Drive.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:24.240
Using Drive apps-- which you
heard a little bit about at

00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:26.530
the keynote, and Josh is going
to show us an awesome demo of

00:06:26.530 --> 00:06:28.010
in a second--

00:06:28.010 --> 00:06:31.140
you can take your apps on the
web, and just edit them with

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:33.320
other web apps that
you've installed.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:36.230
And if there's something that
you want to do on the web that

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:39.450
Google hasn't written a product
to handle, doesn't

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:42.580
matter because chances are
somebody else did and you can

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:44.590
use the file there.

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:48.230
Also, on our Android client you
can, of course, open your

00:06:48.230 --> 00:06:51.060
files using any app that
you've got installed on

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:54.550
Android that can handle those
files, but if you want to use

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:56.780
a web app that you've installed
on the web, our

00:06:56.780 --> 00:06:59.780
Android client can open your
file in that web app on your

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:00.960
mobile device.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:04.200
And with the improvements that
we've made to our mobile API

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.070
if you don't want to have to
go through the hassle of

00:07:06.070 --> 00:07:08.870
downloading your file and
handing it off to another app,

00:07:08.870 --> 00:07:11.840
apps can be written that can
access Google Drive's data

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:13.090
store directly.

00:07:13.090 --> 00:07:17.580
So there's a lot of ways to
continue to use your files

00:07:17.580 --> 00:07:21.050
even when they're stored
on Google Drive.

00:07:21.050 --> 00:07:24.100
And you can reach millions
of users.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:27.740
Google Drive has a lot
of users, I can't

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:29.630
talk specific numbers--

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:30.600
it's more than two.

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:31.860
There's a lot of
guys out there.

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:34.540
And then you're not just getting
access to Google

00:07:34.540 --> 00:07:37.230
Drive's users, you're getting
access to the entire Google

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:42.620
ecosystem of users via things
like OAuth login and all these

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:45.190
different mechanisms that will
bring Google users to your

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:48.070
app, if you build it on
top of Google Drive.

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:53.410
And we are really committed
to helping our developers

00:07:53.410 --> 00:07:57.170
succeed, and there's a lot of
ways that we really think that

00:07:57.170 --> 00:07:59.740
developers can do well
using this API.

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:01.470
So, for example, when--

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:04.020
like almost everything
at Google I/O--

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:06.810
when you use the Google Drive
APIs, you get access to the

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:09.860
entire world of Google APIs,
so it's really easy to

00:08:09.860 --> 00:08:13.800
integrate calendar and
contacts, and all the

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.260
different stuff that we've
already got APIs for, it's

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:18.640
really easy to build that into
your app that's already

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:20.380
talking to Google Drive.

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:23.960
And Google Drive is all
integrated with Google Docs,

00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:27.960
so lots of features that are
features of Google Docs become

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:29.870
ways of publicizing your app.

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:34.210
When you share a document that
was created with your app, the

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:37.700
user gets shared your app too,
or at least an opportunity to

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:38.860
install the app.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:42.169
So your app can grow virally
just through users sharing

00:08:42.169 --> 00:08:44.030
content and collaborating.

00:08:44.030 --> 00:08:46.360
And then, finally, we wanted
to make sure that there was

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:48.840
really every mechanism to
publicize the work you've

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:51.730
done, so we've integrated with
the Chrome Web Store and

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:55.170
there's this entire store where
users can discover new

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:58.260
Google Drive apps and find
out more about what

00:08:58.260 --> 00:08:59.730
you're working on.

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:01.130
Did I forget anything
there, Josh?

00:09:01.130 --> 00:09:02.770
JOSH HUDGINS: I think you've
covered pretty much everything

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:03.470
in the preview.

00:09:03.470 --> 00:09:05.990
JOHN DAY-RICHTER: So here's what
we've launched already--

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:08.210
what we launched before Google
I/O started-- and we wanted to

00:09:08.210 --> 00:09:10.020
just do a brief overview.

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:13.190
So first, there's the
Google Drive API.

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:16.600
So we've completely rebuilt this
from the old Google Docs

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:19.650
List API, which is sort of
similar, but we built it as a

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:21.270
RESTful API--

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:24.410
credentials and authentication
are now based on OAuth 2--

00:09:24.410 --> 00:09:25.370
far more modern--

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:28.110
and we've got client libraries
and code samples in six

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:31.060
different languages, so there
are really a lot of options to

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:34.870
build your app however
you want to.

00:09:34.870 --> 00:09:37.830
JOSH HUDGINS: So as part of the
SDK v1, we also introduced

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:39.520
this concept of a Drive app.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:43.080
So as we were building out Drive
we had built a viewer

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:47.010
that could give you read-only
views of between 30 and 40

00:09:47.010 --> 00:09:49.470
different file types, many of
the major things people like

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:52.190
to view like PDFs, and Word
documents, and images, and

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:53.160
things like that.

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:55.670
We realized there was still this
entire constellation of

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:58.540
content that we just didn't
provide much of an experience

00:09:58.540 --> 00:10:01.710
for, so what we wanted to do
was open up our UI to third

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:04.130
party developers, so they could
take an app that they

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:06.610
had already built that maybe
provided a nice experience for

00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:09.100
a certain type of content and
integrate that app directly

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:11.550
into the Drive UI, and
so that's what Drive

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:13.020
apps are all about.

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:16.530
So you can build an app, and
then you basically tell us

00:10:16.530 --> 00:10:18.760
what sorts of MIME types or
file extensions you can

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:21.750
handle, and once the user
installs that app, we

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:24.450
interweave that app into the
very fabric of the UI, so

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:27.200
everywhere you interact with a
piece of content of that type

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:29.090
users have the choice
of using the app of

00:10:29.090 --> 00:10:30.970
yours that they installed.

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:32.830
We also offer you a neat option,
if you've already

00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:36.350
built a web app that stores
content in its own back end or

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:38.210
some sort of proprietary system,
but you still want to

